-- Regression test: `Char - {'a'}` as a domain, called with 'b' (a value
-- genuinely outside the excluded literal). This caught a real completeness
-- bug during development: comparing `t == mk_Char(n)` directly (with no
-- `from(mk_Char(n)) == n` round-trip fact for the *domain literal's own*
-- 'a', since `membership_constraint` has no solver access to assert one)
-- left cvc5 unable to prove `mk_Char(97) != mk_Char(98)`, so a
-- perfectly valid call to `f('b')` was spuriously reported as a
-- counterexample. Fixed by comparing `from(t) == n` instead, which needs no
-- injectivity fact about `mk_Char` at all (see membership.rs's
-- `literal_element_predicate`).
f : Char - {'a'} -> Char
f(x) = x

main : -> Char
main() = f('b')
